# Architecture Plan

## Repository Shape

This repository will be initialized as a Vite + React + TypeScript frontend application.
The expected top-level structure after issue #1 is:

- `src/`: React application source.
- `src/main.tsx`: React entry point and root render wiring.
- `src/App.tsx`: Initial application shell.
- `src/assets/`: Static assets imported by the application.
- `public/`: Static files served directly by Vite.
- `index.html`: Vite HTML entry point.
- `vite.config.ts`: Vite and React plugin configuration.
- `tsconfig.json`, `tsconfig.app.json`, `tsconfig.node.json`: strict TypeScript configuration.
- `package.json`: scripts and frontend dependencies.

## Shared Types and Modules

No domain model exists yet. Shared TypeScript types should be introduced under
`src/types/` only when a second consumer appears. Component-local types should
remain colocated with the component that owns them.

Future source organization should stay conventional and shallow until the app
has enough surface area to justify deeper boundaries:

- `src/components/` for reusable presentational components.
- `src/hooks/` for reusable React hooks.
- `src/lib/` for framework-agnostic helpers.
- `src/styles/` for global styling if CSS grows beyond the scaffold defaults.

## Issue Dependencies

- Issue #1 has no implementation dependency on other issues.
- Later work should build on the Vite scaffold, npm scripts, and strict
  TypeScript settings created in issue #1.

## Key Design Decisions

- Use Vite's React TypeScript template as the base to minimize custom setup.
- Keep strict TypeScript enabled from the start.
- Prefer standard npm scripts (`dev`, `build`, `preview`, `lint` if scaffolded)
  so CI and local development can rely on common Node tooling.
- Avoid adding routing, state management, UI frameworks, or test tooling until
  a concrete issue requires them.
